ering the debates the case raised about police powers and the legal system.Spanning settings from the Pace's lonely cottage in the Forest of Dean to the House of Commons and using sources ranging from meticulous detective reports to heartfelt admirers’ letters, The most remarkable woman in England combines serious scholarship with vivid storytelling to bring to life the extraordinary lives of ordinary people between the wars.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCriminal procedurezEnglandxHistoryy20th century. 0aTrials (Murder)zEnglandxHistoryy20th century. 7aTRUE CRIME / Murder / General.2bisacsh  aHarry Pace trial.  acelebrity culture.  adramatic homicide trials.  ainstitutional criticism.  ainter-war Britain.  alegal criticism.  apolice investigation.  apolitical criticism.  apost-trial memoirs.  apress sensationalism.  asocial criticism.1 aWood, John Carter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526130785423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526130785/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles